answers.body_markdown:
I don&#39;t believe such a lodash function exists, but a simple utility could be written to provide that behavior:

```
function getFirst(obj, ...paths) {
    for (const path of paths) {
        if (_.has(obj, path)) {
            return _.get(obj, path);
        }
    }
    return;
}
```

No built in function in Lodash allows this (sadly). However, as [Alexander Nied](https://stackoverflow.com/a/58493266/) said in his answer, you can easily create a custom function for this. I will use Lodash functionality instead of vanilla JavaScript just to demonstrate how it can work:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    function getFirst(item, paths) {
      const notFound = Symbol(&quot;not found&quot;);
      
      return _(paths)
        .map(path =&gt; _.get(item, path, notFound))
        .filter(result =&gt; result !== notFound)
        .first();
    }

    const obj = {
      a: {
        b: {
          c: 42
        }
      },
      x: {
        y: 1
      },
      z: 2
    };

    console.log(getFirst(obj, [&#39;g&#39;]));
    console.log(getFirst(obj, [&#39;g&#39;, &#39;h&#39;, &#39;z&#39;]));
    console.log(getFirst(obj, [&#39;g&#39;, &#39;h&#39;, &#39;a.b.c&#39;, &#39;z&#39;]));

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;script src=&quot;https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/lodash@4.17.15/lodash.min.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;


&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

[Chaining](https://lodash.com/docs/4.17.15#lodash) using Lodash is lazily evaluated, so the sequence is map first path to `_.get(item, path)` and if it fails returns a unique `notFound` value. Then if the `notFound` is discarded the next value would be mapped. This continues until either there is a match or all the members of `paths` are exhausted and the value is `undefined`.

