&gt;Can I just manually create a constructor public App(){....} in the application class App.xaml.cs of a WPF project and call a method of a .NET standard class library from there or it may cause an issues later on?

Yes, you can. As mentioned in the [docs](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/programming-guide/classes-and-structs/constructors), if you don&#39;t provide a constructor for your class, C# creates one by default that instantiates the object and sets member variables to the default values. So whenever you want some custom initialization logic, you should define your own constructor.

Depending on what you want to do, it may be a better option to override the `OnStartup` method of the `App` class instead of creating a constructor though:

    public partial class App : Application
    {
        protected override void OnStartup(StartupEventArgs e)
        {
            base.OnStartup(e);
            //your code here...
        }
    }

